06:33.400 --> 06:38.560
What we today call Science Fiction took shape in the pages of the colorful pulp magazines of the 1920s and 30s.

06:38.840 --> 06:42.520
Jack Williamson, who wrote for those pulp magazines, is a living history of science fiction.

06:43.120 --> 06:47.400
His career as a writer goes back to the 1920s, before the term science fiction was even created.

06:47.860 --> 06:50.880
He grew up in the early part of this century on the frontier plains of New Mexico.

06:51.440 --> 06:54.500
Not long after he discovered the fresh and exciting new world of science fiction,

06:54.500 --> 06:59.840
he began selling his work to Hugo Gernsback's Amazing Stories, which was the first science fiction publication.

07:00.340 --> 07:07.300
I grew up on a sand hill farm in the south part of this county when times were pretty grim.

07:10.600 --> 07:18.160
I wanted to be some sort of scientist without any direction or means to get a scientific education.

07:18.160 --> 07:25.960
A few months after Gernsback started, the old Amazing, I came across some copies of it.

07:25.960 --> 07:35.080
And I was immediately fascinated with experiments that worked with travel and time and spaceships to other worlds.

07:36.040 --> 07:38.100
All sorts of wonderful things.

07:38.600 --> 07:42.280
It's been an important share of my life ever since.

07:43.200 --> 07:45.900
The pay scale for early science fiction writers was minimal.

07:45.900 --> 07:48.580
There were no movie rides or paperback contracts.

07:49.040 --> 07:52.040
Yet Williamson was able to produce enough fiction to make a living at it.

07:53.000 --> 08:02.600
Gernsback paid a half a cent of a word or less, which meant, well, you get $25 for a short story and $75 for a novelette.

08:03.340 --> 08:12.880
But Clayton paid two cents a word and up, which is one reason maybe that the Clayton magazines went bankrupt in the Great Depression.

08:12.880 --> 08:28.020
But that meant that I could pound out 4,000 words a day for two days and earn 160 bucks, which was a fabulous feat for a farm kid in depression days.

08:35.980 --> 08:37.800
Amazing Stories was a pulp magazine.

08:38.280 --> 08:39.740
A pulp was printed on cheap paper.

08:39.740 --> 08:45.920
There were usually large format magazines with lurid and colorful illustrations on the cover to catch the attention of prospective readers.

08:46.500 --> 08:56.360
In those days, before the paperbacks and before TV and before the comics, my people read a lot more for entertainment than they do nowadays.

08:57.100 --> 08:59.320
And there were really three sorts of magazines.

08:59.320 --> 09:07.440
There were quality magazines like Harper's and the old Scribner's, Atlantic for people with brains and the slicks,

09:08.000 --> 09:14.060
printed on coated paper that would take good advertising for people with money to spend.

09:14.420 --> 09:18.240
And the pulps for people who had neither brains nor money.

09:18.240 --> 09:24.560
But we had a lot of fun in the pulps even if we were looked down upon widely.

09:25.460 --> 09:34.100
And eventually, science fiction got recognized as being not entirely without brains, let's say.

09:34.560 --> 09:37.820
And nowadays, there's a little bit of money in it sometimes.

09:38.880 --> 09:42.560
A good deal of the early science fiction published in the pulps was space opera,

09:42.560 --> 09:50.240
a term which denotes a melodramatic form of science fiction characterized by heroes and villains, maidens in distress, and intergalactic warfare.

09:50.740 --> 09:56.780
Right, Buck Rogers type stuff. It's unsophisticated but Williamson admires it, and he points at it still around in the movies.

09:57.560 --> 10:01.140
I've never objected to space opera. I still think it's wonderful.

10:01.740 --> 10:08.280
And I even think that Star Wars could have been made out of my legend stories as well as it was from something else.

10:08.280 --> 10:14.020
I enjoyed Star Wars tremendously as a sort of adolescent daydream.

10:14.420 --> 10:21.680
And well, the pulp readers were mostly young and as naive as I was.

10:22.200 --> 10:28.640
And the space opera was a sort of symbolic escape from all sorts of things.

10:35.360 --> 10:43.320
Though it does still turn up now and then, space opera was left behind in science fiction along with Jack Williamson, moved ahead into its golden age.

